<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-102-610  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 102 610.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  Jan 11 1990 v38 n1 p36(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Diffusion welding at low temperatures suits the fine lines ofpower MOSFETs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gosch, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Siemens AG, Munich, West Germany, has developed a new techniquefor bonding silicon power devices to molybdenum substrates.andP;  Thethree-step process uses relatively low temperatures, avoiding thestresses of conventional alloying processes while achieving highthermal-cycling stability and electrically stable contacts withnegligible resistance.andP;  The high temperatures used in alloying cancause warping of device surfaces during cooling because of thedifferent thermal expansion coefficients of molybdenum andsilicon, making the process unsuitable for finely wired devicessuch as power MOSFETs.andP;  The new process places less mechanicalstrain on the devices because the lower temperatures eliminate thedanger of warping during cool-down.andP;  And the process is highlyreproducible, yielding the same results consistently, making itideal for production line use.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MOS Integrated CircuitsField-Effect TransistorsNew TechniqueProductionIntegrated circuits.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>